{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fbbbd4f0-be1a-4118-8046-95d48d74c341","content":"This is a common issue. **.NET MAUI's Android workload bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**, and having `JAVA_HOME` pointing to a different distribution (Adoptium Temurin) causes conflicts during the build.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n1. **Unset `JAVA_HOME`** so the build uses the workload's bundled JDK:\n   ```bash\n   unset JAVA_HOME\n   dotnet build\n   ```\n   To make it permanent, remove the `JAVA_HOME` export from your `~/.zshrc` / `~/.bash_profile`.\n\n2. **Point to the workload's JDK** instead:\n   ```bash\n   # Find the bundled JDK:\n   ls ~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/\n   # Then set JAVA_HOME to the microsoft_dist path found above\n   export JAVA_HOME=~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_serverJRE_17.*/\n   ```\n\n3. **Override per-project** in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>$(Home)/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/microsoft_dist_serverJRE_17.0.12</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n**Option 1 is simplest** — the .NET Android SDK automatically finds its bundled JDK when `JAVA_HOME` isn't set.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7086decc-3901-4c77-9367-14c2f7b1143b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't have specific documentation about this issue. Let me answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI Android builds and Java/JDK requirements.\n\nThe issue is likely that .NET MAUI / Xamarin.Android requires a specific JDK version. Let me think about what's known:\n\n- .NET 8 MAUI requires JDK 17\n- .NET 9 MAUI also requires JDK 17\n- However, the common issue on macOS with Adoptium Temurin is the JAVA_HOME path.\n\nOn macOS, the Adoptium Temurin JDK is typically installed at:\n\n\n`/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`\n\nBut .NET MAUI on macOS specifically looks for the Microsoft OpenJDK that ships with the Android workload, which is installed at a different location. The .NET Android build system has its own JDK detection logic. The most well-known issue is that .NET MAUI ships its own Microsoft OpenJDK as part of the Android workload, so even if you have Temurin installed, the build system might not find it or might prefer the bundled version instead. For .NET 8+ MAUI, JDK 17 is the sweet spot—JDK 11 is too old and JDK 21 can cause problems. The real issue on macOS is likely a path mismatch: Adoptium Temurin installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but the .NET MAUI build system has its own bundled JDK that comes with the workload, and the build might be looking in the wrong place. The real culprit is likely a JDK version mismatch—.NET MAUI bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and having `JAVA_HOME` pointing to a different distribution like Adoptium Temurin can create conflicts during the Android build process. The solution is either unsetting `JAVA_HOME` entirely to let the workload use its bundled JDK, or explicitly pointing it to the Microsoft OpenJDK that ships with the .NET Android SDK. MAUI workload is typically at `/usr/local/share/dotnet/packs/Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Darwin/*/tools/jdk` or similar.\n\nActually, I think the most likely issue here is something different. Let me reconsider the specific version: Temurin 17.0.12.\n\nThe core problem when using Adoptium Temurin with .NET MAUI Android on macOS is that **.NET MAUI's Android workload bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17**, and having `JAVA_HOME` point to a different JDK like Adoptium Temurin can cause build conflicts.\n\nThere are two ways to resolve this: either unset `JAVA_HOME` so the .NET Android SDK uses its bundled JDK, or configure the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property to explicitly point to the workload's bundled JDK instead.","outputTokens":1740,"requestId":"77D3:19D0BE:7CF57E5:8B2C637:69EABDFB"},"id":"845a8e18-3aec-42f7-b3be-026570d2bf41","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:49:31.637Z","parentId":"fa6772d5-f8d8-404e-8941-0983f734adb2"}
